The '''HTR-PM''' is a [[small modular reactor|small modular nuclear reactor]] under development in China. It is a [[high-temperature gas-cooled reactor|high-temperature gas-cooled]] (HTGR) [[pebble-bed reactor|pebble-bed]] [[generation IV reactor|generation IV]] reactor partly based on the earlier [[HTR-10]] prototype reactor.<ref name=zhang2016>{{cite journal |last1=Zhang |first1=Zuoyi |last2=Dong |first2=Yujie |last3=Li |first3=Fu |last4=Zhang |first4=Zhengming |last5=Wang |first5=Haitao |last6=Huang |first6=Xiaojin |last7=Li |first7=Hong |last8=Liu |first8=Bing |last9=Wu |first9=Xinxin |last10=Wang |first10=Hong |last11=Diao |first11=Xingzhong |last12=Zhang |first12=Haiquan |last13=Wang |first13=Jinhua |title=The Shandong Shidao Bay 200 MW e High-Temperature Gas-Cooled Reactor Pebble-Bed Module (HTR-PM) Demonstration Power Plant: An Engineering and Technological Innovation |journal=Engineering |date=March 2016 |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=112–118 |doi=10.1016/J.ENG.2016.01.020 }}</ref> The reactor unit has a thermal capacity of 250 MW, and two reactors are connected to a single steam turbine to generate 210 MW of electricity.<ref name=zhang2016 />
Work on the first demonstration HTR-PM power plant, composed of two reactors driving a single steam turbine, began in December 2012 in [[Shidao Bay Nuclear Power Plant]]. The pressure vessels of the two reactors were installed in 2016, and the plant is expected to start generation in 2018.<ref name="WNN2018">{{cite news |title=First HTR-PM vessel head in place |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-First-HTR-PM-vessel-head-in-place-0401185.html |accessdate=31 May 2018 |work=www.world-nuclear-news.org}}</ref> The HTR-PM is expected to be the first generation IV reactor to enter operation.<ref name="WNN2018" />
