{{Fusion devices |name = JT-60 |type = [[Tokamak]] |operation = 1985–2010 |size = {{convert|3.4|m|sp=us}}/{{convert|1.0|m|sp=us}} |volume = {{convert|90|m3|abbr=on}} |field = 4 [[tesla (unit)|T]] (toroidal) |location = [[Ibaraki Prefecture]], [[Japan]] |}}
'''JT-60''' (short for Japan Torus-60) is large research [[tokamak]], the flagship of [[Japan]]'s [[magnetic fusion]] program, previously run by the [[Japan Atomic Energy Research Institute]] (JAERI) and currently run by the [[Japan Atomic Energy Agency]]'s (JAEA) Naka Fusion Institute in [[Ibaraki Prefecture]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070701014102/http://www.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/NAKA-HPe.html]</ref> It is properly an [[advanced tokamak]], including a D-shaped plasma cross-section and active feedback control.
First designed in the 1970s as the "Breakeven Plasma Test Facility" (BPTF),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iter.org/newsline/179/731 |title=Taking the Big Leap |date=31 May 2011 |website=ITER Newsline |first=Robert |last=Arnoux}}</ref> the goal of the system was to reach [[fusion breakeven|breakeven]], a goal also set for the US's [[TFTR]], the UK's [[Joint European Torus|JET]] and the Soviet T-15. JT-60 began operations in 1985, and like the TFTR and JET that began operations only shortly before it, JT-60 demonstrated performance far below predictions.
Over the next two decades, JET and JT-60 led the effort to regain the performance originally expected of these machines. JT-60 underwent two major modifications during this time, producing JT-60A, and then JT-60U (for "upgrade"). These changes resulted in significant improvements in plasma performance. {{Asof|2018}}, JT-60 currently holds the record for the highest value of the [[fusion triple product]] achieved: {{val|1.77|e=28|u=[[kelvin|K]]·[[second|s]]·m<sup>−3</sup>}} = {{val|1.53|e=21|u=[[electronvolt|keV]]·s·m<sup>−3</sup>}}.<ref name=jt60site>{{cite web|url=http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/index-e.html |title=JT-60 HOME PAGE |publisher=[[Japan Atomic Energy Agency]] |accessdate=5 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208095932/http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/index-e.html |archivedate=8 December 2015 |df= }} </ref><ref name=JT-60-history>[http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/jt60/project/html/history.html JT-60 Operational History and the Progress of Plasma Performance] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223140234/http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/jt60/project/html/history.html |date=2016-02-23 }}</ref>
==JT-60U (Upgrade)==
During [[deuterium]] (D–D fuel) plasma experiments in 1998, plasma conditions were achieved which would have achieved break-even—the point where the power produced by the fusion reactions equals the power supplied to operate the machine—if the D–D fuel were replaced with a 1:1 mix of [[deuterium]] and [[tritium]] (D–T fuel). JT-60 does not have the facilities to handle tritium; only the [[Joint European Torus|JET]] tokamak in the [[United Kingdom]] has such facilities as of 2018. In fusion terminology, JT-60 achieved conditions which in D–T would have provided a [[fusion energy gain factor]] (the ratio of fusion power to input power) ''Q''&nbsp;= 1.25.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/html/exp_rep/rep46.html |title=JT-60U Reaches 1.25 of Equivalent Fusion Power Gain |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106002827/http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/html/exp_rep/rep46.html |archive-date=6 January 2013 |date=7 August 1998 |accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ru/books?id=EGcjCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103&lpg=PT103&dq=JT-60U+q%3D1.2 Daniel Clery. A Piece of the Sun: The Quest for Fusion Energy]</ref><ref>[http://www-pub.iaea.org/mtcd/publications/pdf/csp_001c/pdf/ex1_2.pdf HIGH PERFORMANCE EXPERIMENTS IN JT-60U REVERSED SHEAR DISCHARGES]</ref> A self-sustaining nuclear fusion reaction would need a value of ''Q'' that is greater than 5.<ref name=jt60site/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nstx.pppl.gov/DragNDrop/Five_Year_Plans/2009_2013/NSTX_Research_Plan_2009-2013.pdf|title=NSTX Research Program Five Year Plan for 2009-2013|format=PDF|page=24|publisher=[[National Spherical Torus Experiment]] website|accessdate=5 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euro-fusionscipub.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/JETR99013.pdf|title=The Science Of JET|format=PDF|first1=John|last1=Wesson|publisher=[[EUROfusion]]|date=November 1999|accessdate=5 December 2015}}</ref>
In 2005, ferritic steel (ferromagnet) tiles were installed in the vacuum vessel to correct the magnetic field structure and hence reduce the loss of fast ions.<ref name=long2006>{{cite news release |url=http://www.jaea.go.jp/english/news/p06052303/index.shtml |title=Achievement of long sustainment of a high-confinement, high-pressure plasma in JT-60 - A big step towards extended burn in ITER with the use of ferritic steel - |agency=[[Japan Atomic Energy Agency]] |date=9 May 2006 |accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jaea.go.jp/english/news/p06052303/all.jpg ferromagnet diagrams]</ref> On May 9, 2006, the JAEA announced that the JT-60 had achieved a 28.6 second plasma duration time.<ref name=long2006/> The JAEA used new parts in the JT-60, having improved its capability to hold the plasma in its powerful toroidal magnetic field. The main future objective of JT-60 is to realize high-[[thermodynamic beta|beta]] steady-state operation in the use of reduced radio-activation [[Allotropes of iron|ferritic]] steel in a collision-less regime.
==JT-60SA== It was planned for JT-60 to be disassembled and then upgraded to JT-60SA by adding [[niobium-titanium]] [[superconducting]] coils by 2010.<ref name=jt60site/><ref name=JAR2007>{{cite web|url=http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/annual/07/html/I.JT-60.html#I_3.3 |title=JAEA 2006-2007 annual report |quote="3.1.3 Machine Parameters : A bird's eye view of JT-60SA is shown in Fig. I.3.1-1. Typical parameters of JT-60SA are shown in Table I.3.1-1. The maximum plasma current is 5.5 MA with a relatively low aspect ratio plasma (Rp=3.06 m, A=2.65, κ95=1.76, δ95=0.45) and 3.5 MA for an ITER-shaped plasma (Rp=3.15 m, A=3.1, κ95=1.69, δ95=0.36). Inductive operation with 100s flat top duration will be possible within the total available flux swing of 40 Wb. The heating and current drive system will provide 34 MW of neutral beam injection and 7 MW of ECRF. The divertor target is designed to be water-cooled in order to handle heat fluxes up to15 MW/m2 for long time durations. An annual neutron budget of 4x1021 neutrons is foreseen"}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106154327/http://www-jt60.naka.jaea.go.jp/english/annual/07/html/I.JT-60.html |date=2013-01-06 }} lots of detail on JT-60SA in section 3</ref> It is intended to be able to run with the same shape plasma as [[ITER]].<ref name=JAR2007/>{{rp|3.1.3}} The central solenoid will use [[niobium-tin]] (because of the higher (9 T) field).<ref name=JAR2007/>{{rp|3.3.1}}
Construction of the tokamak officially began in 2013, and will continue until 2020 with first plasma planned in September 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jt60sa.org/b/index_nav_1.htm?n1/introduction.htm |title=The JT-60SA project Introduction |publisher=[[Japan Atomic Energy Agency]] |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>
