{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
In [[computing]], the term '''standby of death''' (also '''SOD''') refers to a problem with some electronic devices where they cannot resume after entering [[Sleep mode|standby]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Toshiba G900 gets patch to fix the "standby of death" bug | url = http://www.intomobile.com/2007/07/23/toshiba-g900-gets-patch-to-fix-the-standby-of-death-bug.html | accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Standby of Death (SOD) with the Tytn II | url = http://forum.xda-developers.com/showthread.php?p=1605798 | accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref><ref>http://forum.xda-developers.com/showthread.php?t=532906</ref> This usually requires the user to forcibly restart the device, typically resulting in the loss of any unsaved work. Although such problems have plagued [[Sleep mode|standby]]-capable devices since their inception, the specific term "standby of death" is relatively new and uncommon.



